{"paragraphs":[{"cues":[{"time":9752,"text":"The phenomenon you saw here for a brief moment"},{"time":14070,"text":"is called quantum levitation and quantum locking."},{"time":20459,"text":"And the object that was levitating here"},{"time":24348,"text":"is called a superconductor."},{"time":26349,"text":"Superconductivity is a quantum state of matter,"},{"time":31941,"text":"and it occurs only below a certain critical temperature."}]},{"cues":[{"time":36198,"text":"Now, it's quite an old phenomenon;"},{"time":38544,"text":"it was discovered 100 years ago."},{"time":40310,"text":"However, only recently,"},{"time":42436,"text":"due to several technological advancements,"},{"time":44798,"text":"we are now able to demonstrate to you"},{"time":47470,"text":"quantum levitation and quantum locking."}]},{"cues":[{"time":51216,"text":"So, a superconductor is defined by two properties."},{"time":57061,"text":"The first is zero electrical resistance,"},{"time":60517,"text":"and the second is the expulsion of a magnetic field from the interior of the superconductor."},{"time":67406,"text":"That sounds complicated, right?"},{"time":70301,"text":"But what is electrical resistance?"},{"time":73173,"text":"So, electricity is the flow of electrons inside a material."},{"time":79422,"text":"And these electrons, while flowing,"},{"time":82771,"text":"they collide with the atoms, and in these collisions"},{"time":85459,"text":"they lose a certain amount of energy."},{"time":87675,"text":"And they dissipate this energy in the form of heat, and you know that effect."},{"time":93276,"text":"However, inside a superconductor there are no collisions,"},{"time":99195,"text":"so there is no energy dissipation."}]},{"cues":[{"time":103887,"text":"It's quite remarkable. Think about it."},{"time":106868,"text":"In classical physics, there is always some friction, some energy loss."},{"time":111947,"text":"But not here, because it is a quantum effect."},{"time":116016,"text":"But that's not all, because superconductors don't like magnetic fields."},{"time":124702,"text":"So a superconductor will try to expel magnetic field from the inside,"},{"time":129019,"text":"and it has the means to do that by circulating currents."},{"time":135142,"text":"Now, the combination of both effects --"},{"time":138132,"text":"the expulsion of magnetic fields and zero electrical resistance --"},{"time":144132,"text":"is exactly a superconductor."}]},{"cues":[{"time":147300,"text":"But the picture isn't always perfect, as we all know,"},{"time":151516,"text":"and sometimes strands of magnetic field remain inside the superconductor."},{"time":158901,"text":"Now, under proper conditions, which we have here,"},{"time":162555,"text":"these strands of magnetic field can be trapped inside the superconductor."},{"time":167645,"text":"And these strands of magnetic field inside the superconductor,"},{"time":173902,"text":"they come in discrete quantities."},{"time":176747,"text":"Why? Because it is a quantum phenomenon. It's quantum physics."},{"time":180393,"text":"And it turns out that they behave like quantum particles."}]},{"cues":[{"time":184243,"text":"In this movie here, you can see how they flow one by one discretely."},{"time":189822,"text":"This is strands of magnetic field. These are not particles,"},{"time":193715,"text":"but they behave like particles."},{"time":198010,"text":"So, this is why we call this effect quantum levitation and quantum locking."}]},{"cues":[{"time":202204,"text":"But what happens to the superconductor when we put it inside a magnetic field?"},{"time":208267,"text":"Well, first there are strands of magnetic field left inside,"},{"time":212852,"text":"but now the superconductor doesn't like them moving around,"},{"time":216972,"text":"because their movements dissipate energy,"},{"time":220420,"text":"which breaks the superconductivity state."},{"time":223366,"text":"So what it actually does, it locks these strands,"},{"time":227724,"text":"which are called fluxons, and it locks these fluxons in place."},{"time":233476,"text":"And by doing that, what it actually does is locking itself in place."},{"time":239764,"text":"Why? Because any movement of the superconductor will change their place,"},{"time":248980,"text":"will change their configuration."}]},{"cues":[{"time":250787,"text":"So we get quantum locking. And let me show you how this works."},{"time":256084,"text":"I have here a superconductor, which I wrapped up so it'd stay cold long enough."},{"time":261844,"text":"And when I place it on top of a regular magnet,"},{"time":266308,"text":"it just stays locked in midair."}]},{"cues":[{"time":270180,"text":"(Applause)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":274245,"text":"Now, this is not just levitation. It's not just repulsion."},{"time":278291,"text":"I can rearrange the fluxons, and it will be locked in this new configuration."},{"time":283412,"text":"Like this, or move it slightly to the right or to the left."},{"time":287436,"text":"So, this is quantum locking -- actually locking -- three-dimensional locking of the superconductor."},{"time":295187,"text":"Of course, I can turn it upside down,"},{"time":297347,"text":"and it will remain locked."}]},{"cues":[{"time":300253,"text":"Now, now that we understand that this so-called levitation is actually locking,"},{"time":309475,"text":"Yeah, we understand that."},{"time":313789,"text":"You won't be surprised to hear that if I take this circular magnet,"},{"time":318051,"text":"in which the magnetic field is the same all around,"},{"time":322019,"text":"the superconductor will be able to freely rotate around the axis of the magnet."},{"time":327955,"text":"Why? Because as long as it rotates, the locking is maintained."},{"time":333979,"text":"You see? I can adjust and I can rotate the superconductor."},{"time":340005,"text":"We have frictionless motion. It is still levitating, but can move freely all around."}]},{"cues":[{"time":346667,"text":"So, we have quantum locking and we can levitate it on top of this magnet."},{"time":355947,"text":"But how many fluxons, how many magnetic strands are there in a single disk like this?"},{"time":362443,"text":"Well, we can calculate it, and it turns out, quite a lot."},{"time":365324,"text":"One hundred billion strands of magnetic field inside this three-inch disk."}]},{"cues":[{"time":372692,"text":"But that's not the amazing part yet, because there is something I haven't told you yet."},{"time":376796,"text":"And, yeah, the amazing part is that this superconductor that you see here"},{"time":382412,"text":"is only half a micron thick. It's extremely thin."},{"time":389937,"text":"And this extremely thin layer is able to levitate more than 70,000 times its own weight."},{"time":399499,"text":"It's a remarkable effect. It's very strong."}]},{"cues":[{"time":405332,"text":"Now, I can extend this circular magnet,"},{"time":408909,"text":"and make whatever track I want."},{"time":413690,"text":"For example, I can make a large circular rail here."},{"time":417619,"text":"And when I place the superconducting disk on top of this rail,"},{"time":424502,"text":"it moves freely."}]},{"cues":[{"time":428611,"text":"(Applause)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":437992,"text":"And again, that's not all. I can adjust its position like this, and rotate,"},{"time":442733,"text":"and it freely moves in this new position."},{"time":449174,"text":"And I can even try a new thing; let's try it for the first time."},{"time":453612,"text":"I can take this disk and put it here,"},{"time":459556,"text":"and while it stays here -- don't move --"},{"time":462540,"text":"I will try to rotate the track,"},{"time":469098,"text":"and hopefully, if I did it correctly,"},{"time":471397,"text":"it stays suspended."}]},{"cues":[{"time":473540,"text":"(Applause)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":482989,"text":"You see, it's quantum locking, not levitation."},{"time":489830,"text":"Now, while I'll let it circulate for a little more,"},{"time":493965,"text":"let me tell you a little bit about superconductors."},{"time":497668,"text":"Now -- (Laughter) --"},{"time":503214,"text":"So we now know that we are able to transfer enormous amount of currents inside superconductors,"},{"time":510237,"text":"so we can use them to produce strong magnetic fields,"},{"time":515460,"text":"such as needed in MRI machines, particle accelerators and so on."},{"time":520646,"text":"But we can also store energy using superconductors,"},{"time":525206,"text":"because we have no dissipation."}]},{"cues":[{"time":527095,"text":"And we could also produce power cables, to transfer enormous amounts of current between power stations."},{"time":534277,"text":"Imagine you could back up a single power station with a single superconducting cable."},{"time":543283,"text":"But what is the future of quantum levitation and quantum locking?"},{"time":547759,"text":"Well, let me answer this simple question by giving you an example."},{"time":554898,"text":"Imagine you would have a disk similar to the one I have here in my hand,"},{"time":561311,"text":"three-inch diameter, with a single difference."},{"time":565190,"text":"The superconducting layer, instead of being half a micron thin,"},{"time":570375,"text":"being two millimeters thin, quite thin."},{"time":573463,"text":"This two-millimeter-thin superconducting layer could hold 1,000 kilograms, a small car, in my hand."},{"time":584198,"text":"Amazing. Thank you."}]},{"cues":[{"time":587494,"text":"(Applause)"}]}]}